The expression **zero-sum game** is used in game theory to explain situations where the victory of one player implies the defeat of another player.

Let's take this idea and take a look at the **Incremental Cash Flows for the Lessor Company** and also at **Incremental Cash Flows for the Leasing Company**:

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Incremental Cash Flows for the Lessee Company}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
&\text{Year }0&\text{Year }1&\text{Year }2&\text{Year }3&\text{Year }4&\text{Year }5\\
\hline
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Aftertax}\\ 
\text{lease}\\ 
\text{payment}
\end{array} &&\footnotesize{-\$1,975}&\footnotesize{-\$1,975}&\footnotesize{-\$1,975}&\footnotesize{-\$1,975}&\footnotesize{-\$1,975}\\
\hline\
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Lost}\\
\text{Depreciation}\\ 
\text{tax shield}
\end{array}&&\footnotesize{-\hspace{10pt}420}&\footnotesize{-\hspace{10pt}420}&\footnotesize{-\hspace{10pt}420}&\footnotesize{-\hspace{10pt}420}&\footnotesize{-\hspace{10pt}420}\\
\hline
