\text{Cash Flow}
\end{array}&\footnotesize{-\$10,000}& \footnotesize{+\$2,395}& \footnotesize{+\$2,395}& \footnotesize{+\$2,395}& \footnotesize{+\$2,395}& \footnotesize{+\$2,395}\\
\hline
\end{array}
$$
<center>Table 2. Incremental Cash Flows for Johnson Leasing.

For the Lessee we have:

$$
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{NPV}_{\text{Lessee}}
&=R_0+\sum_{t=1}^{5} \frac{R_{t}}{(1+i)^{t}}\\[10pt]
&=\$ 10,000-\$ 2,395\sum_{t=1}^{5} \frac{1}{(1+0.05609)^{t}}\\[10pt]
&=\$ 10,000-\$ 2,395\times\left(\frac{1-\dfrac{1}{1.05609^{5}}}{ 0.05609}\right) \\[10pt]
&=\boxed{-\$ 196.83}
\end{align*}
$$

Now, let's take the values in table 2 and calculate the NPV

$$
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{NPV}_{\text{Lessor}}
&=R_0+\sum_{t=1}^{5} \frac{R_{t}}{(1+i)^{t}}\\[10pt]
&=-\$ 10,000+\$ 2,395\sum_{t=1}^{5} \frac{1}{(1+0.05609)^{t}}\\[10pt]
&=-\$ 10,000+\$ 2,395\times\left(\frac{1-\dfrac{1}{1.05609^{5}}}{ 0.05609}\right) \\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$ 196.83}
\end{align*}
$$

Notice that, the amount of money that the lessee **loses** in the lease contract, is the same amount that the lessor **wins**! 

So ***<span style="color: #4257B2">the ${\mathbf{NPV}}$ helps us to illustrate the **zero-sum game** here, where the lease has a positive $\bold{\mathbf{NPV}}$ to one party, and this implies that has a negative $\bold{\mathbf{NPV}}$ to the other</span>***.
